Turn CodeClimate logging back on.Amendment to https://github.com/bellycard/napa/pull/175nnThis line shouldn't have made it in, it was a test to check if this would fixnCodeClimate logging to stderr about how it's not going to do any reporting.nBut I meant to omit it b/c IDK how Code Climate works on Travis.nI'm not even really sure this is the best way to do that.nFor example, an if statement around the require and start might make more sensenthan neutering its logging.nnActually, writing that last sentence just incited me to look at then[docs](http://docs.travis-ci.com/user/ci-environment/#Environment-variables).nAppears that you could just do this:nn```rubynnif ENV['CI'] == 'true'n  require codeclimate-test-reportern  CodeClimate::TestReporter.startnendnn```nnI'll let y'all do that, though, b/c where you report test coverage fromnis a different issue than the test suite swallowing its own output.n
Change napa server alias from c to s.
Add  thor command to start shotgun server.

Hey! Spec suite! Leave them streams alone!Apparently this https://gist.github.com/adamstegman/926858 was to getnRSpec to stfu. But now it calmed down again, so not necessary.nAnd it affects other things, like swallowing print statements,ncausing pry to omit output, and hiding other output that is potentiallynlegitimate.nnHowever, one nice side effect was that it caught other loudmouths in the dragnet:nn* ActiveRecord::Migration, apparently there is a globaly flag you set ton  tell it to shush.n* Thor::Shell... I gave up on this one. Had tried passing in `shell`n  like any sensible interface, but it was blowing up pretty hard. Hadn  tried wiping out here https://github.com/erikhuda/thor/blob/53b3fc89ce750258e19c53b1a99b32dd5941451a/lib/thor/shell.rb#L6n  but it's passing around classes instead of instances, so its like youn  have to have layers on layers of fake classes. Tried passing it heren  https://github.com/erikhuda/thor/blob/53b3fc89ce750258e19c53b1a99b32dd5941451a/lib/thor/shell.rb#L53n  but the indirection of who'se inheriting from whom and calling what onn  what and which vars got set by whatever wherever were just too muchn  for me at this hour, so fuck it. Stub it.n* CodeClimate is logging directly to stderr. You can get it to stfu with:n  `CodeClimate::TestReporter.configuration.logger = Logger.new('/dev/null')`n  Put it before the `CodeClimate::TestReporter.start` I didn't do it b/cn  it was doing this before (it runs before output streams were silenced)n  so I figured maybe someone wanted it that way on purpose. Plus, youn  probaly do want it logging in CI, which you'd probably do by setting ann  env var there, and then silencing it unless you see the var. Since In  don't have access to your CI, and getting all that config wired upn  right tends to be fragile, I figured it'd be best to leave it.nnWent with a matrix theme, b/c the vindictive side of me enjoyed the ideanof Thor's stupid mouth getting melted shut.n

Default rake task runs specsHighly common for Ruby libs to set the default rake task to run the testnsuite. It's the first thing I do when looking at an app. Since its notnbeing used for anything else, figured I'd send a PR to add it.nn* Fix load path before requiring files so that user can type `rake`n  without worrying about Bundler. Otherwise, it fails because it can'tn  find the napa files. Note that not doing this runs the risk ofn  invoking rake without Bundler and accidentally requiring the filesn  from the napa that is installed in your rubygems. Ie those files comingn  from installed version, and other files coming from the dev lib.n  If they sufficiently diverge on a dev's computer, it could cause an  bug that costs the dev a lot of time and frustration.n* Add `rake spec` task to run the test suite. I added my preferredn  options, but modify them at will (figured it was fine sincen  .travis.yml was setting colour)n* Set the default task to depend on the spec task.n
